In a Stern-Gerlach apparatus, electrons with spin $\frac{\pi}{2}$ (left-handed circular polarization) are attracted to the negatively charged plate, while electrons with spin $-\frac{\pi}{2}$ (right-handed circular polarization) are repelled. This results in a net separation of positive and negative charges on opposite sides of the plate. If the beam intensity is low enough, only one electron at a time can pass through the apparatus. Since electrons with $\pm\frac{\pi}{2}$ momentum will require a specific energy to pass through the plate, their contribution to the current will be significantly reduced.
